  }
}

{
  "jurisdiction": "PH",
  "section_id": "110",
  "title": ". Worker preference in case of bankruptcy. In the event of bankruptcy or liquidation of an ",
  "content": ". Worker preference in case of bankruptcy. In the event of bankruptcy or liquidation of an \nemployer’s business, his workers shall enjoy first preference as regards their wages and other monetary \nclaims, any provisions of law to the contrary notwithstanding. Such unpaid wages and monetary claims shall \nbe paid in full before claims of the government and other creditors may be paid. (As amended by Section 1, \nRepublic Act No. 6715, March 21, 1989)",
  "is_repealed": false,
  "metadata": {
    "source_file": "Labor-Code-of-the-Philippines-DOLE.pdf",
    "jurisdiction": "PH",
    "corpus_category": "wages",
    "timestamp": "2026-01-21T14:28:37.636005"
  }
}

{
  "jurisdiction": "PH",
  "section_id": "83",
  "title": ". Normal hours of work. The normal hours of work of any employee shall not exceed eight (8) hours a ",
  "content": ". Normal hours of work. The normal hours of work of any employee shall not exceed eight (8) hours a \nday. \nHealth personnel in cities and municipalities with a population of at least one million (1,000,000) or in hospitals \nand clinics with a bed capacity of at least one hundred (100) shall hold regular office hours for eight (8) hours \na day, for five (5) days a week, exclusive of time for meals, except where the exigencies of the service require \nthat such personnel work for six (6) days or forty-eight (48) hours, in which case, they shall be entitled to an \nadditional compensation of at least thirty percent (30%) of their regular wage for work on the sixth day. For \npurposes of this Article, \"health personnel\" shall include resident physicians, nurses, nutritionists, dietitians, \npharmacists, social workers, laboratory technicians, paramedical technicians, psychologists, midwives, \nattendants and all other hospital or clinic personnel.",
  "is_repealed": false,
  "metadata": {
    "source_file": "Labor-Code-of-the-Philippines-DOLE.pdf",
    "jurisdiction": "PH",
    "corpus_category": "wages",
    "timestamp": "2026-01-21T14:28:37.344293"
  }
}

{
  "jurisdiction": "PH",
  "section_id": "191",
  "title": ". Temporary total disability. ",
  "content": ". Temporary total disability. \na. Under such regulations as the Commission may approve, any employee under this Title who \nsustains an injury or contracts sickness resulting in temporary total disability shall, for each day of \nsuch a disability or fraction thereof, be paid by the System an income benefit equivalent to ninety \npercent of his average daily salary credit, subject to the following conditions: the daily income \nbenefit shall not be less than Ten Pesos nor more than Ninety Pesos, nor paid for a continuous \nperiod longer than one hundred twenty days, except as otherwise provided for in the Rules, and \nthe System shall be notified of the injury or sickness. (As amended by Section 2, Executive Order \nNo. 179) \n   \nb. The payment of such income benefit shall be in accordance with the regulations of the Commission. \n(As amended by Section 19, Presidential Decree No. 850)",
  "is_repealed": false,
  "metadata": {
    "source_file": "Labor-Code-of-the-Philippines-DOLE.pdf",
    "jurisdiction": "PH",
    "corpus_category": "wages",
    "timestamp": "2026-01-21T14:28:38.395414"
  }
}

{
  "jurisdiction": "PH",
  "section_id": "200",
  "title": ". Safety devices. In case the employee’s injury or death was due to the failure of the employer to ",
  "content": ". Safety devices. In case the employee’s injury or death was due to the failure of the employer to \ncomply with any law or to install and maintain safety devices or to take other precautions for the prevention of \ninjury, said employer shall pay the State Insurance Fund a penalty of twenty-five percent (25%) of the lump \nsum equivalent of the income benefit payable by the System to the employee. All employers, specially those \nwho should have been paying a rate of contribution higher than required of them under this Title, are enjoined \nto undertake and strengthen measures for the occupational health and safety of their employees.",
  "is_repealed": false,
  "metadata": {
